<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-what-is-a-weighted-average">What is =
a weighted average?</h2>



<p><strong>The weighted average is the average, or mean, of a data set that=
 gives more weight to some numbers than others.</strong>&nbsp;</p>



<p>Calculate weighted average if some values in a data set are more importa=
nt than others.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Finding your weighted average is more accurate than finding your simple =
average (aka unweighted average), where each data point receives the same =
=E2=80=9Cimportance.=E2=80=9D&nbsp;</p>



<p>Businesses use weighted averages to improve decision-making, cost calcul=
ations, forecasting, and financial analyses.&nbsp;</p>



<p>You might calculate the weighted average for:</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><a href=3D"https://www.patriotsoftware.com/blog/accounting/inventory/">=
<strong>Inventory</strong></a><strong> </strong>to see your average cost pe=
r unit of inventory (especially helpful if you have identical and intertwin=
ed inventory items)</li>



<li><a href=3D"https://www.patriotsoftware.com/blog/accounting/revenue-basi=
cs-small-business/"><strong>Revenue</strong></a><strong> </strong>to see ho=
w different revenue streams contribute to calculations</li>



<li><a href=3D"https://www.patriotsoftware.com/blog/accounting/sales-projec=
tions-small-business-owners/"><strong>Sales forecasting</strong></a><strong=
> </strong>to assign different weights based on historical trends, seasonal=
 changes, or customer demand</li>



<li><strong>Cost of </strong><a href=3D"https://www.patriotsoftware.com/blo=
g/accounting/what-is-capital-your-small-business-accounting-guide/"><strong=
>capital</strong></a><strong> </strong>to see your average from sources lik=
e debt and equity</li>



<li><a href=3D"https://www.patriotsoftware.com/blog/payroll/performance-eva=
luations-made-easy/"><strong>Employee performance evaluations</strong></a><=
strong> </strong>to view a total score with different evaluation criteria w=
eightings</li>
</ul>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-how-to-calculate-weighted-average">H=
ow to calculate weighted average</h2>



<p>You can calculate weighted average with the weighted average formula:</p=
>



<p><strong>Weighted Average</strong> =3D (Sum of the Products of Values and=
 Weights) / Sum of All Weights</p>



<p><strong>Sum of the Products of Values and Weights</strong> =3D Each Valu=
e X Assigned Weight</p>



<figure class=3D"wp-block-table"><table class=3D"has-fixed-layout"><thead><=
tr><th><strong>Use Excel or Google Sheets to calculate weighted average!</s=
trong></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Use the SUMPRODUCT and SUM functions=
 (<a href=3D"https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/office/calculate-an-averag=
e-c68b2803-c6d8-4faf-bea4-02b7c55fe768" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer=
 noopener">Excel</a>) or AVERAGE.WEIGHTED function (<a href=3D"https://supp=
ort.google.com/docs/answer/9084098?hl=3Den" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"norefe=
rrer noopener">Google Sheets</a>).</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>



<p>Confused? We=E2=80=99ll break it down for you step-by-step below.</p>



<div class=3D"schema-how-to wp-block-yoast-how-to-block"><p class=3D"schema=
-how-to-description">How to calculate weighted average:</p> <ol class=3D"sc=
hema-how-to-steps"><li class=3D"schema-how-to-step" id=3D"how-to-step-17424=
07945941"><strong class=3D"schema-how-to-step-name"><strong>Multiply each n=
umber by an assigned weigh</strong>t</strong> <p class=3D"schema-how-to-ste=
p-text">Look at your set of numbers. Assign each number a weight.&nbsp;<br>=
<br>You can assign percentages based on what=E2=80=99s most important to yo=
u. For example, you can assign Product ABC a weight of 60% (0.60) and Produ=
ct XYZ a weight of 40% (0.40).&nbsp;<br><br>Or, you can assign a weight as =
a number of units. For example, you can assign Product ABC a weight of 300 =
units and Product XYZ a weight of 200 units.&nbsp;<br><br>Let=E2=80=99s say=
 Product ABC is $50 and has an assigned weight of 60%. Multiply $50 by 0.60=
. Product XYZ is $25 and has an assigned weight of 40%. Multiply $25 by 0.4=
0.</p> </li><li class=3D"schema-how-to-step" id=3D"how-to-step-174240797608=
1"><strong class=3D"schema-how-to-step-name"><strong>Add all the weighted v=
alues together</strong></strong> <p class=3D"schema-how-to-step-text">After=
 you multiply each number by its assigned weight, you=E2=80=99ll get the =
=E2=80=9Cweighted values.=E2=80=9D Add up all the weighted values together.=
&nbsp;<br><br>For example, Product ABC=E2=80=99s weighted value is $30 ($50=
 X 0.60). Product XYZ=E2=80=99s weighted value is $10 ($25 X 0.40). Add tog=
ether $30 and $10 to get $40.<br></p> </li><li class=3D"schema-how-to-step"=
 id=3D"how-to-step-1742408010539"><strong class=3D"schema-how-to-step-name"=
><strong>Divide the total weighted sum by the total assigned weight value</=
strong></strong> <p class=3D"schema-how-to-step-text">Lastly, add together =
your weights (e.g., the decimals if you used percentages or the units if yo=
u used units). Divide your total weighted sum by the total weight value.<br=
><br>For example, your total weighted sum is $40. Your total assigned weigh=
t value is 1 (0.60 + 0.40). <strong>Your weighted average is $40.</strong><=
/p> </li></ol></div>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-how-do-i-calculate-a-weighted-averag=
e-examples">How do I calculate a weighted average? Examples</h2>



<p>The following examples show how using the weighted average can benefit y=
our business in three areas, revenue, employee performance evaluations, and=
 inventory.&nbsp;</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-1-weighted-average-for-employee-perf=
ormance-evaluation-example">1. Weighted average for employee performance ev=
aluation example</h3>



<p>Let=E2=80=99s say you are evaluating your employee, Vanessa, for her ann=
ual performance review.&nbsp;</p>



<p>You take into account several factors, like work quality and punctuality=
. But some of these factors are more important than others. So, you need to=
 find the weighted average.</p>



<p>Here are the five factors, along with your assigned weight for each:</p>



<ol class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Work quality (40%)</li>



<li>Productivity (35%)</li>



<li>Communication (10%)</li>



<li>Collaboration (10%)</li>



<li>Punctuality (5%)</li>
</ol>



<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding=3D"async" width=3D=
"1024" height=3D"768" src=3D"https://www.patriotsoftware.com/wp-content/upl=
oads/2025/03/weighted-average-formula-chart.webp" alt=3D"Weighted average e=
xample of a performance evaluation." class=3D"wp-image-74601"></figure>



<p>Your factors=E2=80=99 assigned weight must total 100%.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Next, you give Vanessa a score on a scale from 0-100.&nbsp;</p>



<figure class=3D"wp-block-table"><table class=3D"has-fixed-layout"><thead><=
tr><th><strong>Evaluation Factors</strong></th><th><strong>Assigned Weight&=
nbsp;</strong></th><th><strong>Vanessa=E2=80=99s Scores</strong></th></tr><=
/thead><tbody><tr><td>Work quality</td><td>40% (0.40)</td><td>90</td></tr><=
tr><td>Productivity</td><td>35% (0.35)</td><td>90</td></tr><tr><td>Communic=
ation</td><td>10% (0.10)</td><td>60</td></tr><tr><td>Collaboration</td><td>=
10% (0.10)</td><td>60</td></tr><tr><td>Punctuality</td><td>5% (0.05)</td><t=
d>40</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>



<p>If you just found the simple average, Vanessa=E2=80=99s evaluation looks=
 pretty low. She=E2=80=99d receive a 68 out of 100 [(90 + 90 + 60 + 60 + 60=
 + 40) / 5].</p>



<p>But because work quality and productivity are the most important factors=
 to your business, you need to find the weighted average.</p>



<p><strong>Weighted Average =3D</strong> [(90 X 0.4) + (90 X 0.35) + (60 X =
0.10) + (60 X 0.10) + (40 X 0.05)] / [(0.4 + 0.35 + 0.10 + 0.10 + 0.05)]</p=
>



<p><strong>Weighted Average =3D </strong>(36 + 31.5 + 6 + 6 + 2) / 1</p>



<p><strong>Weighted Average =3D </strong>81.5</p>



<p>Vanessa=E2=80=99s evaluation score is 81.5 out of 100 using the weighted=
 average.&nbsp;</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-2-weighted-average-for-revenue-examp=
le">2. Weighted average for revenue example</h3>



<p>Let=E2=80=99s say you have two main sources of revenue: product sales an=
d affiliate marketing. You want to find your weighted average for your tota=
l revenue.</p>



<p>Product sales contribute significantly more revenue to your business tha=
n <a href=3D"https://www.patriotsoftware.com/affiliates/">affiliate marketi=
ng</a>.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Take a look at the revenue for both, along with its assigned weight (aka=
 its contribution to your total revenue):</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Product sales: $80,000 (80%)</li>



<li>Affiliate marketing: $20,000 (20%)&nbsp;</li>
</ul>



<p><strong>Weighted Average</strong> =3D [($80,000 X 0.80) + ($20,000 X 0.2=
0)] / 1</p>



<p><strong>Weighted Average</strong> =3D ($64,000 + $4,000) / 1</p>



<p><strong>Weighted Average</strong> =3D $68,000</p>



<p>This weighted average of $68,000 shows you the combined impact of both p=
roduct sales and affiliate marketing more realistically than a simple avera=
ge. The simple average would show your average revenue is $50,000 [($80,000=
 + $20,000) / 2].</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-3-weighted-average-for-inventory-exa=
mple-nbsp">3. Weighted average for inventory example&nbsp;</h3>



<p>Let=E2=80=99s say you purchased the same inventory, eggs, in different b=
atches and at different prices to sell at your store. You want to find your=
 weighted average for inventory.</p>



<p>Here=E2=80=99s a breakdown of the number of egg cartons you have and the=
 cost per carton:</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Batch 1: 100 cartons at $3.00 per carton</li>



<li>Batch 2: 150 cartons at $4.00 per carton</li>



<li>Batch 3: 200 cartons at $6.00 per carton</li>
</ul>



<p>Your simple average shows the average cost per carton is $4.33 ($3.00 + =
$4.00 + $6.00). But your weighted average tells a more accurate story.</p>



<p><strong>Weighted Average</strong> =3D [(100 X $3.00) + (150 X 4.00) + (2=
00 X $6.00)] / (100 + 150 + 200)</p>



<p><strong>Weighted Average</strong> =3D ($300 + $600 + $1,200) / 450</p>



<p><strong>Weighted Average</strong> =3D $2,100 / 450</p>



<p>The weighed average is $4.67.</p>



